Orchestrates the three-pass entry expansion pipeline that turns parsed dictionary `Entry` ASTs into the `TypedEntry` records both renderers (stroke and text output) consume. The submodules do the real work; this file wires them together and defines the two intermediate record types (`ExpandedEntry`, `TypedEntry`) that flow between passes.

`expand_dict(entries: &[Entry], generic_arg_strokes: Option<&[&str]>) -> Result<Vec<TypedEntry>, ExpandError>` is the single public entry point most callers use instead of invoking the passes directly. It: (1) calls `build_type_set` to collect `@type` entries into a `TypeSet` (named types plus the arity-0 pool used for generic args) — `@type` entries are consumed here and never appear in the output; (2) if `generic_arg_strokes` is `Some`, filters the arity-0 pool down to only those stroke strings, otherwise uses the full pool; (3) runs Pass A (`expand_counts`) over every non-`@type` entry to resolve repeat/dcount/computed counts into concrete chunk templates; (4) runs Pass B (`expand_types_one`) per expanded entry to resolve `%t` type slots against the `TypeOptions`; (5) calls `fix_family_terminals` to patch terminal/bracing flags across sibling entries sharing a stroke family; (6) finishes with `expand_line_flag` to apply the one-liner (U-variant) transformation. Order matters: family-fixing must happen after all types are resolved but before line-flag expansion, since line-flag expansion reads the `terminal` field that family-fixing sets.

`ExpandedEntry` (Pass A output) carries a count-resolved `template: Vec<Chunk>` with no `repeat`/`dcount`/`computed` chunks remaining, plus the resolved `count` and the original `source: Entry`. `TypedEntry` (Pass B output, the final form) adds `terminal: bool` (false means later passes must drop bracing and skip cursor movement for this step), `one_liner: bool` (true means every `%b` in the template collapses instead of breaking — set by the lineflag pass), and `type_label: Option<String>` (the type name chosen at this entry's `%t` slot, or None if there was no type slot). Both structs retain `source: Entry` so downstream code can trace an expansion back to its dictionary line.

Errors from any pass — malformed count expressions, stroke arithmetic overflow, type arity mismatches — all surface as `ExpandError`, defined in `crate::error`. Callers needing finer control (e.g. only Pass A, or type expansion without the full pipeline) should use the re-exported pass functions (`expand_counts`, `expand_all`, `expand_types`, `expand_types_one`, `fix_family_terminals`, `expand_line_flag`, `build_type_set`) directly rather than `expand_dict`.